NS for a project design and/or retrofit alternative is obtained by subtracting the LCC of the alternative (A) from the LCC of the base case (BC), as given by Eq. (10). It is intuitive that NS can also be estimated from differences in individual cost categories as depicted in Eq. (11), or from savings and investments. Positive NS implies that the proposed alternative is cost-effective. While evaluating multiple alternatives, the alternative with lowest LCC will have maximum NS. It is worth noting that LCC and NS can be used interchangeably as they are entirely consistent. NS estimation has an added advantage that the analyst needs to consider only those cost components that are different for the base case and the alternative. However, unlike LCC, estimating NS requires identification of a base case among the alternatives. It should be understood that the base case and the alternative should have the same base date, study period and discount rate.10NS=LCCBC-LCCA\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
